<h1>@HI{{nomi}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}}<strong>@HI{{nomi}}</strong>
<li> <strong>@HI{{nomi}}</strong> @HI{{narazu}} ... @HI{{mo}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{nomi}}</strong> follows a noun and means that there is nothing other than  the thing stated: "only". In this usage
<strong>@HI{{nomi}}</strong> has the same meaning as <a href="grammar-particle-dake.html">@HI{{dake}}</a>, but it is used more in
writing than in the spoken language. <strong>@HI{{nomi}}</strong> can be followed by <a href="graamar-particle-shika.html">@HI{{shika}}<a/>.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{by*means*of^in*front}},kono@KJ{{large^study}}niha@KJ{{make^sex}}<strong>@HI{{nomi}}</strong>shika@KJ{{enter}}renakatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      In the past only men were able to enter this univeristy.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
"A @HI{{<strong>nomi</strong>narazu}}B@HI{{mo}}" is a form used to mean "not only ... but also ...".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{shixe-kusupia}}ha@KJ{{frolic^bend}}<strong>nomi</strong>narazu@KJ{{poem}}motakusan@KJ{{write}}ita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Shakespeare wrote not only plays but many poems as well.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

